LinkedList in Java
`LinkedList` is a class in `java.util` that implements List, Deque, Queue, Collection, and Iterable.
It is a doubly-linked list data structure, meaning each node has references to both its previous and next nodes.
Key Characteristics
- Allows duplicate elements.
- Maintains insertion order.
- Provides constant-time insertion and removal at both ends.
- Slower random access compared to ArrayList (because traversal is required).
- Supports list operations (like ArrayList) plus queue/deque/stack operations.
Categorized Methods
1. Adding Elements
●	`add(E e)` – Appends element at the end.
●	`add(int index, E element)` – Inserts at specific index.
●	`addAll(Collection c)` – Adds all elements from another collection.
●	`addAll(int index, Collection c)` – Inserts all at given index.
●	`addFirst(E e)` – Inserts at the beginning.
●	`addLast(E e)` – Inserts at the end.
●	`offer(E e)` – Adds to the tail (queue style).
●	`offerFirst(E e)` – Adds to the head.
●	`offerLast(E e)` – Adds to the tail.
●	`push(E e)` – Pushes onto stack (front).
2. Accessing Elements
●	`get(int index)` – Returns element at index.
●	`getFirst()` – Returns first element.
●	`getLast()` – Returns last element.
●	`peek()` – Retrieves head without removing.
●	`peekFirst()` – Retrieves first element without removing.
●	`peekLast()` – Retrieves last element without removing.
●	`element()` – Retrieves head (throws exception if empty).
3. Updating Elements
●	`set(int index, E element)` – Replaces element at index.
4. Removing Elements
●	`remove()` – Removes head.
●	`remove(int index)` – Removes element at index.
●	`remove(Object o)` – Removes first occurrence.
●	`removeFirst()` – Removes first element.
●	`removeLast()` – Removes last element.
●	`removeFirstOccurrence(Object o)` – Removes first match.
●	`removeLastOccurrence(Object o)` – Removes last match.
●	`removeAll(Collection c)` – Removes all matching elements.
●	`removeIf(Predicate filter)` – Removes elements satisfying condition.
●	`clear()` – Removes all elements.
●	`poll()` – Retrieves and removes head.
●	`pollFirst()` – Retrieves and removes first.
●	`pollLast()` – Retrieves and removes last.
●	`pop()` – Pops from stack (front).
●	`retainAll(Collection c)` – Keeps only elements present in given collection.
5. Searching & Checking
●	`contains(Object o)` – Checks if element exists.
●	`containsAll(Collection c)` – Checks if all exist.
●	`indexOf(Object o)` – First index of element.
●	`lastIndexOf(Object o)` – Last index of element.
●	`isEmpty()` – Checks if empty.
●	`size()` – Returns number of elements.
●	`equals(Object o)` – Compares with another list.
●	`hashCode()` – Returns hash code.
6. Iteration Methods
●	`iterator()` – Returns iterator.
●	`listIterator()` – Returns list iterator.
●	`listIterator(int index)` – Returns list iterator starting at index.
●	`descendingIterator()` – Returns reverse iterator.
●	`forEach(Consumer action)` – Performs action for each element.
●	`spliterator()` – Returns spliterator.
7. Conversion Methods
●	`toArray()` – Converts to array.
●	`toArray(T[] a)` – Converts to typed array.
8. Queue / Stack Processing
●	`offer(E e)`, `poll()`, `peek()`, `element()`, `push(E e)`, `pop()` – Queue/stack operations.
9. Sublist / View
●	`subList(int fromIndex, int toIndex)` – Returns view of portion.
Java Code Demonstration
import java.util.*;

public class LinkedListDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        LinkedList<String> list = new LinkedList<>();

        // 1. Adding Elements
        list.add("A");
        list.add(1, "B");
        list.addAll(Arrays.asList("C", "D"));
        list.addAll(2, Arrays.asList("E", "F"));
        list.addFirst("Start");
        list.addLast("End");
        list.offer("G");
        list.offerFirst("H");
        list.offerLast("I");
        list.push("StackTop");

        // 2. Accessing Elements
        System.out.println(list.get(2));
        System.out.println(list.getFirst());
        System.out.println(list.getLast());
        System.out.println(list.peek());
        System.out.println(list.peekFirst());
        System.out.println(list.peekLast());
        System.out.println(list.element());

        // 3. Updating Elements
        list.set(2, "Updated");

        // 4. Removing Elements
        list.remove();
        list.remove(1);
        list.remove("C");
        list.removeFirst();
        list.removeLast();
        list.removeFirstOccurrence("E");
        list.removeLastOccurrence("F");
        list.removeAll(Arrays.asList("G", "H"));
        list.removeIf(s -> s.startsWith("U"));
        list.poll();
        list.pollFirst();
        list.pollLast();
        list.pop();
        list.retainAll(Arrays.asList("A", "B", "End"));
        list.clear();

        // 5. Searching & Checking
        System.out.println(list.contains("A"));
        System.out.println(list.containsAll(Arrays.asList("A", "B")));
        System.out.println(list.indexOf("A"));
        System.out.println(list.lastIndexOf("B"));
        System.out.println(list.isEmpty());
        System.out.println(list.size());
        System.out.println(list.equals(new LinkedList<>()));
        System.out.println(list.hashCode());

        // 6. Iteration
        list.addAll(Arrays.asList("X", "Y", "Z"));
        Iterator<String> it = list.iterator();
        while (it.hasNext()) System.out.println(it.next());

        ListIterator<String> lit = list.listIterator();
        while (lit.hasNext()) System.out.println(lit.next());

        ListIterator<String> lit2 = list.listIterator(1);
        while (lit2.hasNext()) System.out.println(lit2.next());

        Iterator<String> descIt = list.descendingIterator();
        while (descIt.hasNext()) System.out.println(descIt.next());

        list.forEach(System.out::println);
        Spliterator<String> spl = list.spliterator();
        spl.forEachRemaining(System.out::println);

        // 7. Conversion
        Object[] arr = list.toArray();
        String[] strArr = list.toArray(new String[0]);

        // 8. Queue/Stack
        list.offer("Queue");
        System.out.println(list.poll());
        System.out.println(list.peek());
        System.out.println(list.element());
        list.push("Stack");
        System.out.println(list.pop());

        // 9. Sublist
        List<String> sub = list.subList(0, 1);
        System.out.println(sub);
    }
}
